00:11:36.245 --> 00:11:36.830
Awakening."

00:11:36.830 --> 00:11:39.192
And I joined here in
New York, actually.

00:11:39.192 --> 00:11:39.900
ALAN SEALES: Wow.

00:11:39.900 --> 00:11:44.520
So this was put on, or, I
guess the revival came on,

00:11:44.520 --> 00:11:45.870
through Deaf West.

00:11:45.870 --> 00:11:47.420
So where did the idea come from?

00:11:47.420 --> 00:11:51.250
Are any of you privy to how
the idea even came about?

00:11:55.630 --> 00:11:57.840
KATIE BOECK: Well, Michael
Arden is our director,

00:11:57.840 --> 00:12:02.040
and I'm pretty sure
that he and Andy, who

00:12:02.040 --> 00:12:05.840
is Hanschen in our cast,
had this brilliant idea

00:12:05.840 --> 00:12:09.830
to do a production of
this show, which centers

00:12:09.830 --> 00:12:14.792
on the themes of basically
the breakdown in communication

00:12:14.792 --> 00:12:16.000
between parents and children.

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:21.380
And how, especially when it
comes to sex and, you know,

00:12:21.380 --> 00:12:24.730
educating children about that
phase of life of adolescence,

00:12:24.730 --> 00:12:28.260
how-- at least in this time
in the show, and even still

00:12:28.260 --> 00:12:31.310
today-- how difficult it can be.

00:12:31.310 --> 00:12:33.070
Because it's uncomfortable,
it's awkward,

00:12:33.070 --> 00:12:35.111
parents don't know how to
talk to their children.

00:12:35.111 --> 00:12:38.290
So they had this amazing
idea to revive it

00:12:38.290 --> 00:12:44.590
with Deaf West, casting two
of the three main characters

00:12:44.590 --> 00:12:48.440
as deaf characters
actually within the show,

00:12:48.440 --> 00:12:51.860
to just sort of amplify
that theme of the difficulty

00:12:51.860 --> 00:12:53.460
in communicating.

00:12:53.460 --> 00:12:56.874
So some of the characters in
the show have deaf parents.

00:12:56.874 --> 00:12:58.290
Some of them have
hearing parents.

00:12:58.290 --> 00:13:05.280
And so in many of the scenes,
that idea of communication

00:13:05.280 --> 00:13:06.475
is really amplified.

00:13:06.475 --> 00:13:09.836
And, I don't know, maybe
you can elaborate on that?

00:13:09.836 --> 00:13:11.294
AUSTIN MCKENZIE:
Well, actually, we

00:13:11.294 --> 00:13:12.953
should talk about
the Milan Conference.

00:13:12.953 --> 00:13:14.786
KATIE BOECK: Oh, yeah,
the Milan Conference.

00:13:18.319 --> 00:13:19.860
SANDRA MAE FRANK
THROUGH INTERPRETER:

00:13:19.860 --> 00:13:23.560
OK, so the Milan Conference
was a gathering that took place

00:13:23.560 --> 00:13:26.290
sometime in the 1880s.

00:13:26.290 --> 00:13:31.470
Back then, the sign language,
ASL, was readily available.

00:13:31.470 --> 00:13:34.170
But at this conference, they
decided to come together

00:13:34.170 --> 00:13:35.530
to talk about communication.

00:13:35.530 --> 00:13:37.279
And they decided that
they would no longer

00:13:37.279 --> 00:13:38.600
allow people to use ASL.

00:13:38.600 --> 00:13:41.800
Instead, they would have to use
an oral means of communication.

00:13:41.800 --> 00:13:43.660
And that way, everybody
would learn English

00:13:43.660 --> 00:13:45.600
and be able to
communicate with everyone.

00:13:45.600 --> 00:13:50.330
And if you wouldn't be able
to use your voice or speak,

00:13:50.330 --> 00:13:52.340
then you wouldn't make
it through education.

00:13:52.340 --> 00:13:55.440
And so that was
happening at the time

00:13:55.440 --> 00:13:57.072
the original play
was being written.

00:13:57.072 --> 00:13:58.530
So it's kind of
interesting to look

00:13:58.530 --> 00:14:00.460
at the parallels
about communication.

00:14:00.460 --> 00:14:01.870
And it fits really perfectly.

00:14:01.870 --> 00:14:03.536
I mean, even though
it wasn't trying to.

00:14:03.536 --> 00:14:05.440
But there's a lot of parallels.

00:14:05.440 --> 00:14:07.880
ALAN SEALES: So how did
the success of the show

00:14:07.880 --> 00:14:09.830
out there lead it
to Broadway now?

00:14:09.830 --> 00:14:14.439
I mean it seems to me--
is that a big leap?

00:14:14.439 --> 00:14:15.980
Or is that kind of
like the next step

00:14:15.980 --> 00:14:19.354
for what it was-- for where
it was out on the west coast?

00:14:19.354 --> 00:14:21.770
ALI STROKER: Yeah, I think
this has been a really special,

00:14:21.770 --> 00:14:25.270
unique situation.

00:14:25.270 --> 00:14:31.130
You know, we put up this
show almost exactly a year.

00:14:31.130 --> 00:14:38.015
Our first show, downtown Los
Angeles, was a year to the day

00:14:38.015 --> 00:14:41.930
that we opened our first
preview on Broadway.

00:14:41.930 --> 00:14:46.770
And we did two different
performances, or productions,

00:14:46.770 --> 00:14:48.780
in LA before we
came to New York.

00:14:48.780 --> 00:14:52.010
We did a production
in a 99-seat theater.

00:14:52.010 --> 00:14:55.160
And it was kind of like
a black box setting.

00:14:55.160 --> 00:14:58.380
It was small and it
was really a time

00:14:58.380 --> 00:15:01.290
for us to explore how we
were going to tell the story.

00:15:01.290 --> 00:15:03.610
And then that went really well.

00:15:03.610 --> 00:15:06.260
We got extended.

00:15:06.260 --> 00:15:07.200
It was sold out.

00:15:07.200 --> 00:15:09.400
People were really,
really excited.

00:15:09.400 --> 00:15:11.540
And then we did it
at a bigger theater

00:15:11.540 --> 00:15:14.710
in Beverly Hills called
the Wallis Annenberg

00:15:14.710 --> 00:15:17.410
theater this past spring.

00:15:17.410 --> 00:15:19.382
And there had been a
little bit of buzz,

00:15:19.382 --> 00:15:21.090
like, oh, maybe it
will move to New York,

00:15:21.090 --> 00:15:22.190
or maybe something will happen.

00:15:22.190 --> 00:15:24.731
And then all of us were like,
we're not getting our hopes up.

00:15:24.731 --> 00:15:25.730
We'll see what happens.

00:15:25.730 --> 00:15:28.190
And then a month
later, we found out

00:15:28.190 --> 00:15:32.100
that we were going to be
opening this fall on Broadway.

00:15:32.100 --> 00:15:33.286
And so, here we are.

