00:16:17.580 --> 00:16:19.038
because this is
amazingly talented.

00:16:19.038 --> 00:16:21.140
[APPLAUSE]

00:16:21.140 --> 00:16:24.530
See, the show was
phenomenal and you guys,

00:16:24.530 --> 00:16:28.450
I would've never thought
that you had never been

00:16:28.450 --> 00:16:30.122
on Broadway before, but--

00:16:30.122 --> 00:16:31.330
ALEX BONIELLO: We fooled you.

00:16:31.330 --> 00:16:32.270
ALAN SEALES: Haha.

00:16:32.270 --> 00:16:34.030
The magic of theater.

00:16:34.030 --> 00:16:37.300
And so, on the surface, the
show is about teenagers,

00:16:37.300 --> 00:16:39.170
and discovering their sexuality.

00:16:39.170 --> 00:16:42.544
And have you found
that a lot of people

00:16:42.544 --> 00:16:44.710
come to the show with
different expectations of what

00:16:44.710 --> 00:16:45.240
it's about?

00:16:45.240 --> 00:16:47.823
Because the friend of mine that
I brought when I saw the show,

00:16:47.823 --> 00:16:49.330
she was like, oh,
it's a tragedy.

00:16:49.330 --> 00:16:51.980
And I said, oh yes,
you just wait, right?

00:16:51.980 --> 00:16:56.100
Do you find that is common
in the feedback that you get?

00:16:56.100 --> 00:16:59.930
ALEX BONIELLO: I'm finding
because the first production

00:16:59.930 --> 00:17:02.610
of the show on Broadway
was kind of recent--

00:17:02.610 --> 00:17:05.690
some would say very
recent-- a lot of people

00:17:05.690 --> 00:17:09.010
have ideas of what this
show is based off of that.

00:17:09.010 --> 00:17:11.349
And I think that when
you come to see the show,

00:17:11.349 --> 00:17:14.067
you realize what we
and our creative team,

00:17:14.067 --> 00:17:15.900
and what Michael Arden
and everybody decided

00:17:15.900 --> 00:17:18.420
to do with it is a complete
reinvention of what

00:17:18.420 --> 00:17:19.260
the show is, right?

00:17:19.260 --> 00:17:21.780
I mean, by setting
these characters,

00:17:21.780 --> 00:17:25.895
making them actually deaf, it's
not like a theatrical conceit

00:17:25.895 --> 00:17:27.020
that there's sign language.

00:17:27.020 --> 00:17:29.356
You know, it's actually
part of the story now.

00:17:29.356 --> 00:17:30.980
And I think that the
second that people

00:17:30.980 --> 00:17:33.550
who have any kind of expectation
as to what the show is

00:17:33.550 --> 00:17:37.280
sees what's going on and your
brain takes a minute to adjust,

00:17:37.280 --> 00:17:39.391
you're like, OK, so I'm
listening to that person,

00:17:39.391 --> 00:17:41.390
but I'm going to watch
the person who's signing.

00:17:41.390 --> 00:17:43.170
Then once everything
clicks, I think

00:17:43.170 --> 00:17:45.740
you understand what it is
that we're trying to do.

00:17:45.740 --> 00:17:48.290
And I think overall,
the reception

00:17:48.290 --> 00:17:49.770
has been overwhelmingly
positive.

00:17:49.770 --> 00:17:52.020
And that feels very
good for all of us.

00:17:52.020 --> 00:17:52.990
I'm sure.

00:17:52.990 --> 00:17:53.781
ALAN SEALES: Right.

00:17:53.781 --> 00:17:55.850
Well, what was that
translation process like?

00:17:55.850 --> 00:17:57.984
How did you approach
this, or the director?

00:17:57.984 --> 00:18:00.150
How did you approach this
and say, all right, here's

00:18:00.150 --> 00:18:02.900
this amazingly well put
together, finalized show?

00:18:02.900 --> 00:18:06.080
And then kind of
open up the surface,

00:18:06.080 --> 00:18:08.174
put the sign language
aspect on top of it,

00:18:08.174 --> 00:18:09.590
and then put it
all back together?

00:18:09.590 --> 00:18:13.140
Because in my opinion,
the original choreography

00:18:13.140 --> 00:18:14.390
had a lot of hand movement.

00:18:14.390 --> 00:18:16.280
Obviously none of it
had to do with signing,

00:18:16.280 --> 00:18:19.010
but a lot of that
original integrity

00:18:19.010 --> 00:18:21.090
is still maintained
in your production,

00:18:21.090 --> 00:18:24.950
even though the
entire show is signed.

00:18:24.950 --> 00:18:28.360
AUSTIN MCKENZIE: I think that
going through the translation

00:18:28.360 --> 00:18:34.210
process-- we have four
genius translators.

00:18:34.210 --> 00:18:37.150
Let's see, their names,
Linda Bove, Shoshannah Stern,

00:18:37.150 --> 00:18:39.880
Anthony Natale, and
Elizabeth Greene,

00:18:39.880 --> 00:18:44.810
and they're all geniuses at what
they've done with the script.

00:18:44.810 --> 00:18:49.250
All of the scenes, and
the time period, is 1891.

00:18:49.250 --> 00:18:56.760
So all of that is almost old
signs that were used back then.

00:18:56.760 --> 00:18:58.080
But all of the music is--

00:18:58.080 --> 00:19:01.330
ALAN SEALES: So the
signing-- ASL progresses?

00:19:01.330 --> 00:19:04.190
SANDRA MAE FRANK THROUGH
INTERPRETER: If I may,

00:19:04.190 --> 00:19:05.780
I can expand on
that a little bit.

00:19:05.780 --> 00:19:08.300
So just like English
has changed over time,

00:19:08.300 --> 00:19:12.860
and it grows and develops, and
some words aren't used anymore,

00:19:12.860 --> 00:19:15.660
and new words come in-- the
same thing with sign language.

00:19:15.660 --> 00:19:19.630
And so there are different
signs that we use.

00:19:19.630 --> 00:19:23.750
I mean, we still do use
modern terms throughout.

00:19:23.750 --> 00:19:27.010
But there are some signs
that are done differently

00:19:27.010 --> 00:19:28.930
as an homage to that time.

00:19:28.930 --> 00:19:30.720
It's the way we
produce the sign.

00:19:30.720 --> 00:19:34.450
I mean, the 1890s was a
more uptight kind of area.

00:19:34.450 --> 00:19:38.670
So we try to reflect
that in the language

00:19:38.670 --> 00:19:41.830
and sign in a proper
manner and what would

00:19:41.830 --> 00:19:43.520
have been done at that time.

00:19:43.520 --> 00:19:45.520
ALAN SEALES: Proper--
wow, that is something

00:19:45.520 --> 00:19:46.436
I never thought about.

00:19:50.369 --> 00:19:51.910
KATIE BOECK: The
original production,

00:19:51.910 --> 00:19:54.510
though, really made a
distinction between the time

00:19:54.510 --> 00:19:56.950
period being very-- the
language being very proper

00:19:56.950 --> 00:20:00.220
in the scenes, and the songs
themselves sort of taking you

00:20:00.220 --> 00:20:03.330
out of that time to this
modern rock musical score.

00:20:03.330 --> 00:20:08.490
So that was a big distinction
in the original show.

00:20:08.490 --> 00:20:10.430
So the fact that
that's being reflected

00:20:10.430 --> 00:20:13.780
in the sign in this show,
and with the band being

00:20:13.780 --> 00:20:17.970
on stage in this show, I think
that is one aspect that we've

00:20:17.970 --> 00:20:20.560
been able to really-- because
we know the show is totally

00:20:20.560 --> 00:20:22.010
different, we're doing a
completely different thing

00:20:22.010 --> 00:20:23.176
than we did in the original.

00:20:23.176 --> 00:20:25.160
But that aspect of
it, I think, is really

00:20:25.160 --> 00:20:28.245
being maintained
in this production.

00:20:28.245 --> 00:20:30.370
ALAN SEALES: So how much
of what is signed actually

00:20:30.370 --> 00:20:31.970
corresponds to
what is being sung?

00:20:31.970 --> 00:20:34.152
Are the lyrics maintained
in the sign language?

00:20:34.152 --> 00:20:35.693
SANDRA MAE FRANK
THROUGH INTERPRETER:

00:20:35.693 --> 00:20:38.485
No, no, it's
completely different.

00:20:38.485 --> 00:20:39.610
It is completely different.

00:20:43.040 --> 00:20:45.431
AUSTIN MCKENZIE: When it comes
to the words of the music,

00:20:45.431 --> 00:20:47.180
I mean, as I was saying
before, the scenes

00:20:47.180 --> 00:20:48.850
are all pretty straightforward.

00:20:48.850 --> 00:20:50.150
The words, they make sense.

00:20:50.150 --> 00:20:51.950
It's regular communication.

00:20:51.950 --> 00:20:54.940
But when the songs come
about, they're very poetic.

00:20:54.940 --> 00:21:00.322
And it's almost Shakespearean.

00:21:00.322 --> 00:21:01.780
You might not
understand completely

00:21:01.780 --> 00:21:03.910
what they're saying just
hearing it the first time.

00:21:03.910 --> 00:21:05.326
You really have
to think about it.

00:21:05.326 --> 00:21:08.780
It really challenges
the audience members.

00:21:08.780 --> 00:21:13.110
And so with our translators,
the four translators,

00:21:13.110 --> 00:21:18.410
they did a brilliant job
with duplicating that essence

00:21:18.410 --> 00:21:20.740
of beauty and poetry.

00:21:20.740 --> 00:21:24.080
And it's still in sign language.

00:21:24.080 --> 00:21:26.470
But you know, like
many languages,

00:21:26.470 --> 00:21:27.990
the word order is different.

00:21:27.990 --> 00:21:30.450
So you'll be singing a
word, but maybe you're

00:21:30.450 --> 00:21:31.920
not signing that word.

00:21:31.920 --> 00:21:35.240
Maybe it's flipped int a
different part of the sentence.

00:21:35.240 --> 00:21:37.410
Just structurally,
I mean, that's

00:21:37.410 --> 00:21:41.486
syntaxually a thing that's not
very exciting to talk about.

00:21:41.486 --> 00:21:49.530
But the essence of the
songs, of the poetry,

00:21:49.530 --> 00:21:51.040
is still in the sign language.

00:21:51.040 --> 00:21:52.860
Daniel, did you want to--?

00:21:52.860 --> 00:21:53.084
DANIEL DURANT
THROUGH INTERPRETER:

00:21:53.084 --> 00:21:54.000
No, you're doing fine.

00:21:54.000 --> 00:21:55.800
You said it all.

00:21:55.800 --> 00:21:57.341
SANDRA MAE FRANK
THROUGH INTERPRETER:

00:21:57.341 --> 00:21:59.440
You know what, I will
say, as an example,

00:21:59.440 --> 00:22:04.220
there's a line from the song
that we did that-- I'm just

00:22:04.220 --> 00:22:04.970
going to sign it.

00:22:04.970 --> 00:22:08.580
But the line that
talks about signing,

00:22:08.580 --> 00:22:10.260
and that I would do a new dance.

00:22:10.260 --> 00:22:11.410
OK that's the ASL.

00:22:11.410 --> 00:22:14.710
So it's not exactly what
the English is going to be,

00:22:14.710 --> 00:22:17.840
but this is what it looks like.

00:22:17.840 --> 00:22:20.500
KATIE BOECK: Here is
Sorrow doing a new dance.

00:22:20.500 --> 00:22:22.041
SANDRA MAE FRANK
THROUGH INTERPRETER:

00:22:22.041 --> 00:22:25.100
So instead of following exactly
what the English words are,

00:22:25.100 --> 00:22:26.940
we go for more of the concepts.

00:22:26.940 --> 00:22:34.060
And so once people see what
the signs are, and they're

00:22:34.060 --> 00:22:37.480
hearing the words, even if they
don't understand each one right

00:22:37.480 --> 00:22:39.240
away, it all comes together.

00:22:39.240 --> 00:22:43.270
And I feel like the ASL adds
a whole strong layer that

00:22:43.270 --> 00:22:46.460
makes it oh so very visual.

00:22:46.460 --> 00:22:50.580
ALAN SEALES: So talking
about, I guess, the union

00:22:50.580 --> 00:22:53.360
between actor and
voice actor who

00:22:53.360 --> 00:22:55.810
is also a band
member-- that adds,

00:22:55.810 --> 00:22:58.010
like, two extra
layers, in my opinion,

00:22:58.010 --> 00:23:00.600
to what's going on here.

00:23:00.600 --> 00:23:03.150
Was the rehearsal
process, or was

00:23:03.150 --> 00:23:06.519
the discovery and the creation
of the character different,

00:23:06.519 --> 00:23:08.060
do you think, than
that would've been

00:23:08.060 --> 00:23:11.950
if you had been approaching
a character on your own?

00:23:11.950 --> 00:23:14.180
ALEX BONIELLO: Well,
ours is particularly fun

00:23:14.180 --> 00:23:16.490
because, like I said, I
joined the second run.

00:23:16.490 --> 00:23:19.610
So he had already done
all this work, right,

00:23:19.610 --> 00:23:22.070
on what his idea of
this character was.

00:23:22.070 --> 00:23:26.680
And I-- up until, like, a day
before we started rehearsals--

00:23:26.680 --> 00:23:28.820
I had never even
met a deaf person.

00:23:28.820 --> 00:23:33.010
So we had absolutely no means
of communication whatsoever.

00:23:33.010 --> 00:23:35.030
So when Daniel and
I met, it started

00:23:35.030 --> 00:23:38.400
with him using his
phone to type to me,

00:23:38.400 --> 00:23:42.470
which is the only thing
I had to talk to him.

00:23:42.470 --> 00:23:45.062
And so through that,
we would sit down,

00:23:45.062 --> 00:23:47.020
we would look at the
script, and before we even

00:23:47.020 --> 00:23:50.100
talked about character choice or
what this character's feeling,

00:23:50.100 --> 00:23:53.230
he would show me
all these signs.

00:23:53.230 --> 00:23:57.700
And you know, I may
not be able to know

00:23:57.700 --> 00:24:00.210
exactly what it is that he's
signing in all of our scenes

00:24:00.210 --> 00:24:00.950
together.

00:24:00.950 --> 00:24:02.610
But him and I have
worked really,

00:24:02.610 --> 00:24:05.110
really hard, and
with the ASL masters,

00:24:05.110 --> 00:24:09.060
to make sure that we
understand that when he's

00:24:09.060 --> 00:24:11.780
on this part of the
sequence of sign language,

00:24:11.780 --> 00:24:14.700
that means I have to be on this
word, and things like that.

00:24:14.700 --> 00:24:17.640
And then comes the whole
discussion of sitting down

00:24:17.640 --> 00:24:20.857
and Daniel will tell me,
this is what is going on

00:24:20.857 --> 00:24:21.690
with this character.

00:24:21.690 --> 00:24:28.490
Because it's, I would say, like
a 70%-30% collaboration here.

00:24:28.490 --> 00:24:33.160
The physical actor needs
to be the one taking lead.

00:24:33.160 --> 00:24:35.789
And it needs to be
our job to support

00:24:35.789 --> 00:24:36.830
what it is they're doing.

00:24:36.830 --> 00:24:39.246
But, you know, again, that
doesn't mean there's not input.

00:24:39.246 --> 00:24:42.224
And I'm sure Daniel has plenty
to say about this as well.

00:24:42.224 --> 00:24:43.890
DANIEL DURANT THROUGH
INTERPRETER: Sure.

00:24:43.890 --> 00:24:44.470
Right.

00:24:44.470 --> 00:24:50.297
I think that I don't have
any musical lines at first.

00:24:50.297 --> 00:24:51.380
We didn't start with that.

00:24:51.380 --> 00:24:53.920
But he can see the
emotion, the energy

00:24:53.920 --> 00:24:56.750
and then when it comes to music,
he kind of takes the lead.

00:24:56.750 --> 00:24:59.240
And so I follow his
timing and where he

00:24:59.240 --> 00:25:01.770
is with the rhythm and whatnot.

00:25:01.770 --> 00:25:03.410
Because I can't hear it at all.

00:25:03.410 --> 00:25:06.260
So we use cues for one
another, and right, I

00:25:06.260 --> 00:25:08.760
take the lead when it's
a non-musical part.

00:25:08.760 --> 00:25:11.120
And then I follow
his lead otherwise.

00:25:11.120 --> 00:25:12.140
And it is a challenge.

00:25:12.140 --> 00:25:14.480
I mean, I don't have a lot
of experience with music,

00:25:14.480 --> 00:25:17.930
and I need to learn when to go
faster or when to go slower.

00:25:17.930 --> 00:25:20.560
There are different instruments
used at different times.

00:25:20.560 --> 00:25:22.867
So these are things
we've worked on together.

00:25:22.867 --> 00:25:24.450
ALEX BONIELLO: And
you actually saw it

00:25:24.450 --> 00:25:26.074
when we were singing
our song together.

00:25:26.074 --> 00:25:28.350
If you notice, I
was tapping myself

00:25:28.350 --> 00:25:31.320
just so that he knew when a
certain line was starting.

00:25:31.320 --> 00:25:32.950
Because in the
context of the show,

00:25:32.950 --> 00:25:35.324
there's a lot more going on,
obviously, than just the two

00:25:35.324 --> 00:25:37.900
of us standing there and
me being able to watch him.

00:25:37.900 --> 00:25:40.840
There are lights and things
like that that will help him

00:25:40.840 --> 00:25:42.257
and then--

00:25:42.257 --> 00:25:44.840
ALAN SEALES: What other kind of
cues do the rest of the actors

00:25:44.840 --> 00:25:45.120
use?

00:25:45.120 --> 00:25:45.280
DANIEL DURANT
THROUGH INTERPRETER:

00:25:45.280 --> 00:25:46.860
Well, the choreography
has really

00:25:46.860 --> 00:25:48.800
worked with how we're
moving on the stage.

00:25:48.800 --> 00:25:51.220
There may be a prop
that's handed off,

00:25:51.220 --> 00:25:55.700
or some other movement
or action on the stage,

00:25:55.700 --> 00:25:58.000
so that each of us know
that, OK, that's my cue.

00:25:58.000 --> 00:26:00.770
When that happens, she takes
a paper, then I do this.

00:26:00.770 --> 00:26:02.145
AUSTIN MCKENZIE:
I will say, too,

00:26:02.145 --> 00:26:05.630
that I think in this production,
it's not so much of--

00:26:05.630 --> 00:26:07.130
and I think it
started off this way,

00:26:07.130 --> 00:26:09.530
but as we all kind of grew
together and understood--

00:26:09.530 --> 00:26:11.240
and even Michael, I
think, as he started

00:26:11.240 --> 00:26:14.900
to explore this and understand,
really, what the show was--

00:26:14.900 --> 00:26:17.690
I really feel like the
voice actors aren't just

00:26:17.690 --> 00:26:18.260
voice actors.

00:26:18.260 --> 00:26:20.480
I think you guys are
your own characters.

00:26:20.480 --> 00:26:25.170
People have equated them to the
subconscious of the deaf actor,

00:26:25.170 --> 00:26:26.850
or imaginary friends.

00:26:26.850 --> 00:26:28.360
I see them as guardian angels.

00:26:28.360 --> 00:26:29.950
And it was even a
couple weeks ago

00:26:29.950 --> 00:26:33.660
when I have a very
intimate scene with Sandra,

00:26:33.660 --> 00:26:40.020
and I didn't realize that
Katie was making choices

00:26:40.020 --> 00:26:41.780
and communicating with Sandra.

00:26:41.780 --> 00:26:45.527
And I think it's really--
I wish I could see that,

00:26:45.527 --> 00:26:46.610
because it's so beautiful.

00:26:46.610 --> 00:26:49.010
KATIE BOECK: I think that speaks
to the creative part of working

00:26:49.010 --> 00:26:49.350
together.

00:26:49.350 --> 00:26:51.183
Because obviously there
are technical things

00:26:51.183 --> 00:26:53.850
like making sure her
signs are the same amount

00:26:53.850 --> 00:26:55.260
of time as my line.

00:26:55.260 --> 00:26:56.820
So that's a very
technical thing.

00:26:56.820 --> 00:26:59.310
Or squeezing her
shoulder so that she

00:26:59.310 --> 00:27:02.650
knows that-- you know-- we
don't have anything like that.

00:27:02.650 --> 00:27:05.496
I squeeze his shoulder, but
for her, any time I touch her,

00:27:05.496 --> 00:27:06.210
it's a cue.

00:27:06.210 --> 00:27:08.990
I'm not just touching her
arbitrarily to touch her.

00:27:08.990 --> 00:27:14.992
It's because I'm trying to
cue her within the song.

00:27:14.992 --> 00:27:17.200
So that's all the technical
side of working together.

00:27:17.200 --> 00:27:18.574
And then creatively,
I think this

00:27:18.574 --> 00:27:22.390
is a really interesting point,
because we have a relationship

00:27:22.390 --> 00:27:23.740
on stage, you know?

00:27:23.740 --> 00:27:25.820
There are things
we do to ourselves,

00:27:25.820 --> 00:27:28.860
you know, in our
own lives that I

00:27:28.860 --> 00:27:33.310
now, as her voice and sort of
her subconscious, her guardian

00:27:33.310 --> 00:27:36.130
angel-- her angel on
her right, her devil

00:27:36.130 --> 00:27:40.460
on her left, whatever--
I'm guiding her

00:27:40.460 --> 00:27:41.870
as sort of a big sister figure.

00:27:41.870 --> 00:27:44.930
And that, from a creative,
artistic standpoint,

00:27:44.930 --> 00:27:48.835
is really cool, because I get to
embody some of her subconscious

00:27:48.835 --> 00:27:51.210
thoughts that-- as an actor,
you have an inner monologue.

00:27:51.210 --> 00:27:52.668
If you take an
acting class, people

00:27:52.668 --> 00:27:54.310
will say, you're
speaking your lines,

00:27:54.310 --> 00:27:56.160
but what are you saying
underneath all that?

00:27:56.160 --> 00:27:59.540
And I really get the
opportunity to explore

00:27:59.540 --> 00:28:02.010
those kinds of feelings.

00:28:02.010 --> 00:28:04.950
And if you see the show, there's
moments where we connect.

00:28:04.950 --> 00:28:08.064
And it's funny, because
she's looking to me, like,

00:28:08.064 --> 00:28:09.480
should I go talk
to this cute boy?

00:28:09.480 --> 00:28:11.771
And I'm like yeah, yeah, you
should totally go do that.

00:28:11.771 --> 00:28:14.100
Or, should I have sex
with this cute boy?

00:28:14.100 --> 00:28:15.557
And I'm like, uh.

00:28:15.557 --> 00:28:21.290
And what's interesting is,
part of my exciting process

00:28:21.290 --> 00:28:25.280
has been using
the lyric as a way

00:28:25.280 --> 00:28:27.610
to inform this relationship.

00:28:27.610 --> 00:28:31.150
So many of the songs are in
a past tense, which-- that's

00:28:31.150 --> 00:28:33.180
just what the writer gave us.

00:28:33.180 --> 00:28:38.090
And so for me, trying to justify
why I'm here on this stage--

00:28:38.090 --> 00:28:39.730
starting at the
beginning, I really

00:28:39.730 --> 00:28:43.640
wanted to allow Sandy to create
this character for herself,

00:28:43.640 --> 00:28:47.630
and without a lot of influence
from the voice inside her head.

00:28:47.630 --> 00:28:50.920
I wanted her to have that
opportunity, so I would only

00:28:50.920 --> 00:28:52.606
really step in in
terms of, like, here's

00:28:52.606 --> 00:28:53.980
what I think this
character would

00:28:53.980 --> 00:28:57.560
do if we reached a point of,
what would this character do?

00:28:57.560 --> 00:29:00.050
If we really needed to kind
of collaborate on that.

00:29:00.050 --> 00:29:04.080
But so much of that has
been honoring her choices,

00:29:04.080 --> 00:29:05.980
allowing her to be
free within the moment.

00:29:05.980 --> 00:29:09.030
Because there's so many
technical aspects, in order

00:29:09.030 --> 00:29:12.550
for her to feel like I can
make new choices every night,

00:29:12.550 --> 00:29:16.680
it's really on me to be
focused and following her.

00:29:16.680 --> 00:29:19.800
If she wants to take more
time on a certain line,

00:29:19.800 --> 00:29:21.900
I can't just do my own thing.

00:29:21.900 --> 00:29:23.884
I really have to watch
what she's doing.

00:29:23.884 --> 00:29:25.300
And going back to
the point I made

00:29:25.300 --> 00:29:27.008
about the lyrics being
in the past tense,

00:29:27.008 --> 00:29:29.270
for me, being
outside of it, it's

00:29:29.270 --> 00:29:33.030
really been this experience
of a remembrance, almost.

00:29:33.030 --> 00:29:36.610
Like, I go through the
show and I'm almost

00:29:36.610 --> 00:29:42.466
remembering what my former
self, the choices she's made.

00:29:42.466 --> 00:29:46.105
And it has become sort of like
a spiritual aspect of the show.

00:29:46.105 --> 00:29:47.771
I think a lot of
people come to our show

00:29:47.771 --> 00:29:50.270
and feel like, wow, that was--
because so many of the themes

00:29:50.270 --> 00:29:53.920
are religious and spiritual,
and about how the Church has

00:29:53.920 --> 00:29:58.890
caused so many people to feel so
ashamed of their human desires.

00:29:58.890 --> 00:30:02.170
And so I think having
these voiced in characters

00:30:02.170 --> 00:30:05.190
has really amplified
that spiritual element

00:30:05.190 --> 00:30:07.046
of the show, at least for me.

