ALAN SEALES: Yeah,
it's very ironic.

00:32:39.020 --> 00:32:40.853
You're also the first
person in a wheelchair

00:32:40.853 --> 00:32:42.328
to ever be on Broadway as well.

00:32:42.328 --> 00:32:45.316
[APPLAUSE]

00:32:47.310 --> 00:32:51.270
ALAN SEALES: So yes,
lots of firsts here.

00:32:51.270 --> 00:32:54.725
But I want to go
back to the-- what

00:32:54.725 --> 00:32:56.477
do we call it-- people
swapping, whenever

00:32:56.477 --> 00:32:57.560
there are understudies in.

00:32:57.560 --> 00:33:00.389
And that's why, Robert, that's
where you come in, right?

00:33:00.389 --> 00:33:01.930
So how many people
do you understudy?

00:33:01.930 --> 00:33:04.300
AUSTIN MCKENZIE: He just
went in for our Hanschen

00:33:04.300 --> 00:33:06.050
a couple nights ago,
and he was brilliant.

00:33:06.050 --> 00:33:06.920
He was genius.

00:33:06.920 --> 00:33:08.170
ALAN SEALES: And so he should.

00:33:10.830 --> 00:33:13.534
And so how many characters
do you understudy?

00:33:13.534 --> 00:33:15.325
ROBERT ARIZA: I cover
four different roles.

00:33:18.150 --> 00:33:22.150
I have also never swung before
I started this production,

00:33:22.150 --> 00:33:24.160
and all of the
characters that I cover

00:33:24.160 --> 00:33:27.560
sign the entirety of the show.

00:33:27.560 --> 00:33:29.559
AUSTIN MCKENZIE:
It's an easy job.

00:33:29.559 --> 00:33:31.350
ROBERT ARIZA: I've also
never swung before.

00:33:31.350 --> 00:33:34.360
I've been an understudy
before, for like one character

00:33:34.360 --> 00:33:36.720
in a show or
something, but swinging

00:33:36.720 --> 00:33:40.440
for several different roles is
definitely its own challenge.

00:33:40.440 --> 00:33:42.640
And I feel like I
was very lucky enough

00:33:42.640 --> 00:33:50.020
to come to this point in my
life very prepared for this job,

00:33:50.020 --> 00:33:53.040
because I have done two
different productions of Spring

00:33:53.040 --> 00:33:54.300
Awakening prior to this.

00:33:54.300 --> 00:33:58.280
And actually, right before I
got my audition for this job,

00:33:58.280 --> 00:34:01.190
I had just closed a production
of Spring Awakening upstate

00:34:01.190 --> 00:34:02.860
where I was playing Melchior.

00:34:02.860 --> 00:34:06.840
So it was fresh in my mind,
and I was ready to audition.

00:34:06.840 --> 00:34:08.449
And then they called
me back and they

00:34:08.449 --> 00:34:10.449
had me do an ASL work session.

00:34:10.449 --> 00:34:12.904
And it was two hours of
intense, like, OK, you're

00:34:12.904 --> 00:34:15.320
going to learn a scene and a
song for your final callback,

00:34:15.320 --> 00:34:18.090
and then kind of prove to
us that you can learn ASL

00:34:18.090 --> 00:34:18.800
fast enough.

00:34:23.719 --> 00:34:26.394
And it's really hard, because
like they were mentioning

00:34:26.394 --> 00:34:28.560
before, a lot of this cast
has been together already

00:34:28.560 --> 00:34:31.370
for a year, developing
the show and everything,

00:34:31.370 --> 00:34:37.340
and the swings-- I think
almost all of us are new.

00:34:37.340 --> 00:34:40.889
We had to learn it just from
watching them in rehearsal.

00:34:40.889 --> 00:34:44.710
We didn't really get any special
attention until after opening.

00:34:44.710 --> 00:34:46.889
So our first rehearsal
was the Tuesday

00:34:46.889 --> 00:34:49.951
after we opened on Broadway.

00:34:49.951 --> 00:34:51.909
ALAN SEALES: That's like
a week and a half ago.

00:34:51.909 --> 00:34:54.480
ROBERT ARIZA: Yeah.

00:34:54.480 --> 00:34:58.000
I had really only one actual
rehearsal for Hanschen

00:34:58.000 --> 00:35:01.030
before I went on, because
I went on Monday night.

00:35:01.030 --> 00:35:06.080
And I had never been
so under-rehearsed

00:35:06.080 --> 00:35:08.450
for a performance ever
in my entire life.

00:35:08.450 --> 00:35:12.880
And I've been in performing
for 11 years now.

00:35:12.880 --> 00:35:15.920
But the support that I got
from the cast and everyone

00:35:15.920 --> 00:35:19.170
backstage, the crew, everyone
was watching out for me.

00:35:19.170 --> 00:35:20.835
Whenever I was just
a little bit off,

00:35:20.835 --> 00:35:22.460
I would get a little
shove from someone

00:35:22.460 --> 00:35:24.180
to make sure I was
in the right spot.

00:35:24.180 --> 00:35:27.859
It was very, very
shoved with love.

00:35:27.859 --> 00:35:29.900
Every time I came off
stage people were like, OK,

00:35:29.900 --> 00:35:30.700
how are you feeling?

00:35:30.700 --> 00:35:31.325
How's it going?

00:35:31.325 --> 00:35:33.630
And I was like, good, good.

00:35:33.630 --> 00:35:36.010
It was just the craziest night.

00:35:36.010 --> 00:35:38.680
KATIE BOECK: He also had 100
people in the audience to see,

00:35:38.680 --> 00:35:39.800
which was amazing.

00:35:39.800 --> 00:35:40.070
We have an incredible cast.

00:35:40.070 --> 00:35:41.528
ROBERT ARIZA: So
I'm from New York.

00:35:41.528 --> 00:35:42.355
I'm from Queens.

00:35:42.355 --> 00:35:45.950
And being from New York, I've
lived here all of my life,

00:35:45.950 --> 00:35:49.480
and my family and friends
are all here, basically.

00:35:49.480 --> 00:35:52.990
And so I knew that I
had the date on Monday,

00:35:52.990 --> 00:35:56.420
that was going to be
my first night on,

00:35:56.420 --> 00:35:58.170
from the day I got the job.

00:35:58.170 --> 00:36:01.100
And so I told people right
away, get your tickets

00:36:01.100 --> 00:36:02.090
for October 5th.

00:36:02.090 --> 00:36:04.130
That's my Broadway debut.

00:36:04.130 --> 00:36:10.676
And word got around, and I
had about 150 people there

00:36:10.676 --> 00:36:13.490
to see me.

00:36:13.490 --> 00:36:16.964
It was the wildest
night of my life.

00:36:16.964 --> 00:36:19.130
ALAN SEALES: Looks like we
got a question over here.

00:36:19.130 --> 00:36:20.556
AUDIENCE: Hi, I just
recently saw the show.

00:36:20.556 --> 00:36:21.170
It was great.

00:36:21.170 --> 00:36:23.010
I was curious if you could
explain the beginning where

00:36:23.010 --> 00:36:24.240
you are all in
your undergarments

00:36:24.240 --> 00:36:25.568
and the significance of that.

00:36:28.835 --> 00:36:29.960
ALEX BONIELLO: I'm clothed.

00:36:29.960 --> 00:36:31.320
I don't--

00:36:31.320 --> 00:36:31.820
AUSTIN MCKENZIE:
That's true, yeah.

00:36:31.820 --> 00:36:33.361
KATIE BOECK: I think
it's basically--

00:36:33.361 --> 00:36:38.844
Michael wanted it
to be like, not--

00:36:38.844 --> 00:36:40.510
he didn't want there
to be a time period

00:36:40.510 --> 00:36:41.560
to be clear on stage.

00:36:41.560 --> 00:36:43.010
And at the end of the
show, everyone also

00:36:43.010 --> 00:36:44.010
takes their undergarments off.

00:36:44.010 --> 00:36:46.660
So it's really this time where
we come on stage as ourselves,

00:36:46.660 --> 00:36:48.000
and we leave as ourselves.

00:36:48.000 --> 00:36:48.825
And without--

00:36:48.825 --> 00:36:50.700
AUSTIN MCKENZIE: We take
our clothes off back

00:36:50.700 --> 00:36:52.039
to undergarments.

00:36:52.039 --> 00:36:53.080
KATIE BOECK: Right, yeah.

00:36:53.080 --> 00:36:53.930
In the last song--

00:36:53.930 --> 00:36:55.500
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:36:55.500 --> 00:36:58.330
KATIE BOECK: We don't
get naked or anything.

00:36:58.330 --> 00:36:59.920
We're not nude on stage.

00:36:59.920 --> 00:37:02.530
That's a different musical.

00:37:02.530 --> 00:37:07.070
But we all have-- everyone
except for the musicians,

00:37:07.070 --> 00:37:09.144
which I think is a cool
picture at the end, too.

00:37:09.144 --> 00:37:10.185
We're in modern clothing.

00:37:10.185 --> 00:37:13.420
The musicians are all in
modern clothing the whole time,

00:37:13.420 --> 00:37:15.540
but the undergarments,
I think, serve

00:37:15.540 --> 00:37:19.300
as just a wiping away of time.

00:37:19.300 --> 00:37:21.800
It's not about it
being set in that time.

00:37:21.800 --> 00:37:25.430
It's these themes
are relevant today.

00:37:25.430 --> 00:37:29.559
Parents and children still
have trouble communicating.

00:37:29.559 --> 00:37:31.600
That's why there's this
big outrage about Planned

00:37:31.600 --> 00:37:34.120
Parenthood-- people
need other places to go

00:37:34.120 --> 00:37:37.030
to get this information,
because parents sometimes don't

00:37:37.030 --> 00:37:38.780
know how to talk to their kids.

00:37:38.780 --> 00:37:42.599
And so I think that just
really serves as a device.

00:37:42.599 --> 00:37:44.390
ALI STROKER: I'd like
to add something too.

00:37:44.390 --> 00:37:47.330
This show is really
an ensemble piece.

00:37:47.330 --> 00:37:51.580
We work together so closely,
not just the technical sides

00:37:51.580 --> 00:37:55.400
of the signing, but we
have to all be together.

00:37:55.400 --> 00:37:59.525
And so that is a moment
before the show starts

00:37:59.525 --> 00:38:01.130
where we're all
on stage together,

00:38:01.130 --> 00:38:04.310
and we can connect like,
OK, here we go, team.

00:38:04.310 --> 00:38:05.530
Let's tell the story.

00:38:05.530 --> 00:38:09.260
Let's connect with each
other before we do this.

00:38:09.260 --> 00:38:12.577
So I think it also serves
as a moment for all of us.

00:38:12.577 --> 00:38:14.660
KATIE BOECK: Right, and
then when Sandy and I come

00:38:14.660 --> 00:38:17.370
to the mirror, she
hands me my guitar

00:38:17.370 --> 00:38:20.610
and I hand her her
dress, her period dress.

00:38:20.610 --> 00:38:22.830
And so I think
that really serves

00:38:22.830 --> 00:38:24.530
as a technique to
just illustrate

00:38:24.530 --> 00:38:27.190
how the show's going to work.

00:38:27.190 --> 00:38:30.840
She gives me the
permission to be her voice,

00:38:30.840 --> 00:38:34.000
and I give her permission to
go forth and to tell the story.

00:38:34.000 --> 00:38:36.040
And that ends up
setting the stage

00:38:36.040 --> 00:38:37.880
without having to
have someone explain.

00:38:37.880 --> 00:38:41.040
That does it for that.

00:38:41.040 --> 00:38:43.700
ALAN SEALES: So you guys are all
on stage as the house is open,

00:38:43.700 --> 00:38:45.033
like the audience is loading in.

00:38:47.580 --> 00:38:49.540
How much of that is
choreographed and scripted?

00:38:49.540 --> 00:38:51.760
Or are you guys actually
just up there having fun

00:38:51.760 --> 00:38:53.280
and being yourselves?

00:38:53.280 --> 00:38:53.630
SANDRA MAE FRANK
THROUGH INTERPRETER:

00:38:53.630 --> 00:38:54.740
We're just playing.

00:38:54.740 --> 00:38:58.240
We're just having fun with each
other, warming up together.

00:38:58.240 --> 00:38:59.740
Yeah, it's really
been a great thing

00:38:59.740 --> 00:39:01.330
because it helps us to relax.

00:39:01.330 --> 00:39:03.720
It helps us to know
we're coming together--

00:39:03.720 --> 00:39:04.691
we're working together.

00:39:04.691 --> 00:39:06.190
And I don't know
about other people,

00:39:06.190 --> 00:39:08.350
but for me it was
like, OK, I'm ready.

00:39:08.350 --> 00:39:09.100
Here we are.

00:39:09.100 --> 00:39:10.710
I'm putting on this character.

00:39:10.710 --> 00:39:13.400
And so no, nothing
of it is planned out.

00:39:13.400 --> 00:39:15.730
It's our playing ground
before the show starts.

00:39:15.730 --> 00:39:17.240
AUSTIN MCKENZIE: It also makes
you a little less scared,

00:39:17.240 --> 00:39:18.700
because that
nightmare where you're

00:39:18.700 --> 00:39:22.065
in front of the class with
just your underwear on?

00:39:22.065 --> 00:39:25.230
Well, we did it, so.

00:39:25.230 --> 00:39:26.517
Every night.

00:39:26.517 --> 00:39:28.600
ALAN SEALES: Have you ever
had any weird happening

00:39:28.600 --> 00:39:29.650
where you had to hold
the house, and you're

00:39:29.650 --> 00:39:32.130
sitting there on stage for
like 10 minutes saying,

00:39:32.130 --> 00:39:33.922
why can't I put
my clothes on yet?

00:39:33.922 --> 00:39:35.130
ALEX BONIELLO: Opening night.

00:39:35.130 --> 00:39:36.088
ALAN SEALES: Oh really?

00:39:36.088 --> 00:39:38.790
ALEX BONIELLO: Yeah, a lot
of people who were very fancy

00:39:38.790 --> 00:39:40.820
had to arrive.

00:39:40.820 --> 00:39:44.560
We knew that was
going to be the deal,

00:39:44.560 --> 00:39:47.130
but you're just standing there.

00:39:47.130 --> 00:39:50.332
You're trying to be
in the show and not

00:39:50.332 --> 00:39:52.540
be too excited, because it's
opening night and stuff,

00:39:52.540 --> 00:39:54.414
but then you're like,
ah, there's Kelly Ripa.

00:39:54.414 --> 00:39:55.376
Hello.

00:39:55.376 --> 00:39:57.126
People are getting
dressed, and then we're

00:39:57.126 --> 00:40:01.340
standing there trying to--
but it hasn't been that bad.

00:40:01.340 --> 00:40:04.590
KATIE BOECK: It's t-shirts and
boxers, and slips for girls,

00:40:04.590 --> 00:40:07.900
so old-timey underwear
is more conservative

00:40:07.900 --> 00:40:12.180
than modern underwear,
which is nothing.

00:40:15.139 --> 00:40:16.930
ALAN SEALES: I'll go
back to the underlying

00:40:16.930 --> 00:40:19.320
message of the
show for a second,

00:40:19.320 --> 00:40:23.200
because in the show
you deal with suicide,

00:40:23.200 --> 00:40:26.320
and with teenage pregnancy
and abortion, and just

00:40:26.320 --> 00:40:30.640
overall general topics
that now are still

00:40:30.640 --> 00:40:33.010
somewhat taboo, unfortunately.

00:40:33.010 --> 00:40:36.560
Have you had anyone reach out
to you through the show, maybe,

00:40:36.560 --> 00:40:40.310
that has voiced
support through you,

00:40:40.310 --> 00:40:43.450
or looked for support from you?

00:40:43.450 --> 00:40:45.530
DANIEL DURANT THROUGH
INTERPRETER: Well, yeah.

00:40:45.530 --> 00:40:47.625
One of the favorite parts
that I've experienced

00:40:47.625 --> 00:40:50.350
is afterwards, going
out to meet the fans,

00:40:50.350 --> 00:40:52.286
and sign the autographs,
and talk to people.

00:40:52.286 --> 00:40:53.660
And there have
been people who've

00:40:53.660 --> 00:40:57.490
approached me and talked about
their own personal experiences.

00:40:57.490 --> 00:41:01.020
And it's just fantastic
to see the variations

00:41:01.020 --> 00:41:05.830
amongst our fans, but the common
threads and the similarities--

00:41:05.830 --> 00:41:08.890
the experience of coming through
a dark time and depression.

00:41:08.890 --> 00:41:12.050
And for people to be able
to see that on stage,

00:41:12.050 --> 00:41:14.430
that has been inspiring
to me to honor that,

00:41:14.430 --> 00:41:17.620
and hope that we're reflecting
that in an honorable way.

00:41:17.620 --> 00:41:19.520
But yeah, it has
been, to me, to meet

00:41:19.520 --> 00:41:21.070
the fans and the
various emotions

00:41:21.070 --> 00:41:24.530
that this generates, people
who have experienced loss.

00:41:24.530 --> 00:41:26.264
It's a pretty human experience.

00:41:26.264 --> 00:41:27.805
SANDRA MAE FRANK
THROUGH INTERPRETER:

00:41:27.805 --> 00:41:31.140
And I would also add that
we've gotten letters,

00:41:31.140 --> 00:41:34.170
or people on Twitter
or Tumblr, and even

00:41:34.170 --> 00:41:36.430
some personal direct emails.

00:41:36.430 --> 00:41:41.560
There was one story that a
woman sent about having grown up

00:41:41.560 --> 00:41:44.580
hearing and having become deaf
and having to try and learn

00:41:44.580 --> 00:41:47.090
sign language, and she
hadn't really gotten into it.

00:41:47.090 --> 00:41:49.020
But by virtue of
seeing the show,

00:41:49.020 --> 00:41:50.940
she felt like
there may have been

00:41:50.940 --> 00:41:52.700
an opening in our
community, and that she

00:41:52.700 --> 00:41:55.740
felt motivated to go out
there and learn sign language.

00:41:55.740 --> 00:41:58.460
She's deaf, and there's
lots of people out there

00:41:58.460 --> 00:42:00.460
who lose their
hearing, but they try

00:42:00.460 --> 00:42:02.110
to get through just
with reading lips

00:42:02.110 --> 00:42:03.739
and without learning
sign language.

00:42:03.739 --> 00:42:05.030
And they never are comfortable.

00:42:05.030 --> 00:42:07.020
They never have 100% access.

00:42:07.020 --> 00:42:09.320
And so for us to
represent that experience,

00:42:09.320 --> 00:42:11.150
that was kind of
heart-wrenching for me.

00:42:11.150 --> 00:42:11.981
That was touching.

00:42:11.981 --> 00:42:14.230
ALI STROKER: And I'd just
like to add one other thing.

00:42:14.230 --> 00:42:15.855
I've had some really
cool conversations

00:42:15.855 --> 00:42:19.540
with people in the disabled
or differently-abled community

00:42:19.540 --> 00:42:23.570
about how rarely the two topics
of sexuality and disability

00:42:23.570 --> 00:42:24.830
are put together.

00:42:24.830 --> 00:42:27.210
And that this is a
really unique opportunity

00:42:27.210 --> 00:42:31.060
to be able to share
that story, when you

00:42:31.060 --> 00:42:32.990
add this other element onto it.

00:42:36.570 --> 00:42:39.350
AUSTIN MCKENZIE: I think
the biggest thing is--

00:42:39.350 --> 00:42:41.550
so many people come
into this show, I think,

00:42:41.550 --> 00:42:47.470
ignorant to this culture that's
alive and well and beautiful,

00:42:47.470 --> 00:42:49.664
and I don't think
that it's a tragedy

00:42:49.664 --> 00:42:50.830
to be ignorant to something.

00:42:50.830 --> 00:42:53.440
I think the real tragedy is when
you continue to be ignorant,

00:42:53.440 --> 00:42:55.231
and you choose to be
ignorant to something.

00:42:55.231 --> 00:42:57.490
And I think that
for people who have

00:42:57.490 --> 00:43:02.090
seen the show who are deaf,
or-- it really doesn't matter.

00:43:02.090 --> 00:43:04.880
I mean, for any audience
member in the show, I think,

00:43:04.880 --> 00:43:08.930
seeing this production this
way, it's putting forth the idea

00:43:08.930 --> 00:43:11.020
that there is a
place for everyone.

00:43:11.020 --> 00:43:12.900
Regardless of anything
that has to do

00:43:12.900 --> 00:43:17.170
with your physical challenges,
everyone has something.

00:43:17.170 --> 00:43:19.150
And there's a place for
every single person.

00:43:19.150 --> 00:43:19.490
ALAN SEALES: Right.

00:43:19.490 --> 00:43:21.989
Well the closing number that
you guys performed here for us,

00:43:21.989 --> 00:43:25.342
"Purple Summer"-- purple
summer is a flower that

00:43:25.342 --> 00:43:26.550
only blooms in summer, right?

00:43:26.550 --> 00:43:29.160
And I think that's what-- it's
supposed to be metaphorical?

00:43:29.160 --> 00:43:29.990
Or is it a literal thing?

00:43:29.990 --> 00:43:31.270
AUSTIN MCKENZIE: It's beautiful.

00:43:31.270 --> 00:43:32.907
ALAN SEALES: So it's this
flower that only blooms

00:43:32.907 --> 00:43:34.920
in the summer, which I
took to interpret-- this

00:43:34.920 --> 00:43:36.420
is me reading into
it-- which I took

00:43:36.420 --> 00:43:40.630
to interpret as the spring,
everything is just blossoming.

00:43:40.630 --> 00:43:42.890
Everything is growing,
but everything

00:43:42.890 --> 00:43:44.220
is pretty much time boxed.

00:43:44.220 --> 00:43:47.330
So if things are bad, that
basically this too shall

00:43:47.330 --> 00:43:49.970
pass, like, it will get better.

00:43:49.970 --> 00:43:50.770
Time moves on.

00:43:50.770 --> 00:43:51.730
Time heals all wounds.

00:43:51.730 --> 00:43:54.600
ROBERT ARIZA: And I think
that's one thing, and through

00:43:54.600 --> 00:43:57.040
every iteration of this
show that I've done before--

00:43:57.040 --> 00:43:59.860
and I was a huge fan of the
original when it came out.

00:43:59.860 --> 00:44:02.850
And it came out a
time where I was

00:44:02.850 --> 00:44:05.980
going through a lot of things
that this show just shed light

00:44:05.980 --> 00:44:07.520
on.

00:44:07.520 --> 00:44:09.030
It just helped me through.

00:44:09.030 --> 00:44:11.570
It was like the soundtrack
of my life at the time.

00:44:11.570 --> 00:44:13.797
And one thing that's
always been consistent,

00:44:13.797 --> 00:44:15.630
one message that has
always been consistent,

00:44:15.630 --> 00:44:18.250
is that as tragic
as the story is,

00:44:18.250 --> 00:44:21.180
when you get to "Purple Summer,"
it's that message of hope.

00:44:21.180 --> 00:44:23.640
You have to leave the audience
with that message of hope,

00:44:23.640 --> 00:44:25.280
that there is more.

00:44:25.280 --> 00:44:28.190
That there is a light at
the end of all of this.

00:44:28.190 --> 00:44:32.750
And "Purple Summer" is not meant
to be an ending to the story.

00:44:32.750 --> 00:44:33.600
It's a coda.

00:44:33.600 --> 00:44:35.700
In the script, it's
written as a coda.

00:44:35.700 --> 00:44:38.310
The story ends at the end
of Melchior's last song,

00:44:38.310 --> 00:44:38.830
as you know.

00:44:38.830 --> 00:44:42.840
And then the actors come out and
tell you what the message is,

00:44:42.840 --> 00:44:45.860
of why we told you the story.

00:44:45.860 --> 00:44:48.400
AUSTIN MCKENZIE: You
need to experience winter

00:44:48.400 --> 00:44:50.690
to get to summer.

00:44:50.690 --> 00:44:53.090
ALAN SEALES: Good point.

00:44:53.090 --> 00:44:55.370
All right, so if there
are no more questions,

00:44:55.370 --> 00:44:57.550
then we are out of time here.

00:44:57.550 --> 00:45:02.320
So please help me in
thanking them for coming in.

00:45:02.320 --> 00:45:04.680
